Rating: 4
This is a great recipe with several steps but easy to substitute with ingredients you have on hand. I had frozen whiting fillets, which I thought would spell disaster because the meat could be so delicate and may fall apart while frying. It worked very well though if you don't flip the fillets around too much! One flip is enough. I substituted apple cider vinegar for the rice vinegar in the pickled onions, then added a bay leaf, peppercorns and italian seasonings then poured through strainer afterwards (didn't want any broken fillings or gagging with stray peppercorns!) Also, instead of adding jalapeños to the onions, I added a teaspoon of finely diced scotch bonnet (habanero) pepper, which probably equaled the heat of the 5 jalapeños!! Thought Baja Cream was too thick so added buttermilk. Also, didn't want to overdo it on the tanginess so didn't add lime to cream as salsa and onions would be tangy so added flavor like cayenne, paprika, powdered chipotle, white pepper and tarragon and salt to cream - was delicious!! Kept the tomatillo salsa as is - great basic recipe by the way. Didn't have time to marinate the fish, but did have buttermilk so made a basic batter by combining 1 cup of buttermilk and one egg, more spices, hot sauce (no cilantro or lemon - i heard these create nasty burnt bits in the oil?) I dipped fillets in batter, dredged them in a combination of flour, bread crumbs, salt and pepper, and fried in vegetable oil. I served these fish tacos with small flour tortillas, which I find much tastier than corn when serving fish. I also wish I had finely chopped cabbage or romaine to serve with these tacos and some sliced radishes. I think that would make the recipe even better!!

Rating: 4
Exceptional Fare!! I dont give many 4 fork ratings but this one desrves one.

Rating: 4
Everybody went back for seconds for this when I made it for a party. I paired it with the mango-corn-jicama salad found on this website. Here are my suggestions: 1) Make salsas the day before so the flavors can blend 2) omit the salt in the fish breading. The self rising flour has enough sodium and the fish can be salted immediately after it leaves the fryer if it needs more. 3) The SEASONED rice vinegar added a lot of the flavor to the pickle. Do not subsititute, but one 12 oz bottle is enough. As the pickle forms, it extracts liquid from the onions and peppers. 4) Flour tortillas are always preferred to corn for ease of prep and holding a taco together. 5) But since you have a hot fryer, make your own tortilla chips with the corn tortillas to munch on beforehand. 6) The mango-corn- jicama salad recipe can easily be and should be reduced. The recipe as is serves more 12 servings.

