Rating: 4
i made these for the super bowl this past sunday. i used mahi mahi, as halibut was unavailable, and white wine vinegar in the pickled onions and peppers. also substituted olive oil for vegetable oil, and flour tortillas instead of corn. everything was so delicious, and i'm already planning on making these again the next time i'm in the states! i'll have to grow my own jalepenos, tomatillos, and cilantro if i want to make these here in greece. it would be worth it!

Rating: 3
We really enjoyed this. I used red snapper. The pickled onions and peppers are great. Based on other reviews, I skipped the mayo in the Baja cream and used low fat sour cream. It was very good. The only change I would make next time is to roast all the tomatillas rather than put half in the oven. I will be making this again.

Rating: 4
Delicious! the fish was amazing - had some fresh halibut - folks were just eating it off the platter as it came out of the oil. Made fresh corn tortillas. Also omitted the mayo from the cream, as others have noted. Onions were great - I misread the directions and just added 1 sliced jalapeno instead of the whole ones. The spicy fans loved the pickled pepper.

Rating: 4
Wow, what a perfect fish taco recipe! I do have to say that I followed timmylulu's advice on the Baja Sauce. I only added a squirt of mayo and added a little more lime juice. It made the Baja Sauce the talk of my party! Also, I used less vegetable oil, about 1/2 inch deep, to fry the fish in. We had chips and salsa on the side & I MUST recommend the drink I had: HERBALTINI found at http://food.sunset.com/sunset/recipefinder.dyn?action=displayRecipe&recipe_id=1119564. Happy Cooking!

